    "prompt": "<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows an equipotential map for a system of 3 point charges. Two of the point charges are located near the top of the map, not quite at the same height, and the third point charge is located near the bottom of the map. Around each point charge there are several nearly-concentric circles. Farther away from the point charges, the equipotential curves get less circular. The equipotential curves around the two charges at the top of the map are roughly peanut shaped. The equipotential curves around the charge at the bottom of the map are roughly elliptical. Near the middle of the map, the 0 kilovolt equipotential curve is mostly straight, sloping slightly up and to the right. The first circle around the point charge at the bottom of the map is a positive 5 kilovolt equipotential curve, and Point B is indicated on it. The first circle around one of the point charges at the top of the map is a negative 5 kilovolt equipotential curve. Point A is indicated on the third circle around that same point charge. There are two equipotential curves between Point A and the 0 kilovolt equipotential curve, and there are 4 equipotential curves between Point B and the 0 kilovolt equipotential curve.\" src=\"/images/7d1f05ebcfa2a315da71fe9823d09d30.svg\"></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A map of equipotential lines for a system of point charges is shown in the figure, where the potential difference is the same between each pair of adjacent lines. What is the magnitude of the potential difference between points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></span></span>?</p>\n",
